### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Adam bought 3 kilograms of nuts and 2.5 kilograms of dried fruits at a store. One kilogram of nuts costs $12 and one kilogram of dried fruit costs $8. How much did his purchases cost?<n>Output: 56<n><n>Input: Johns goes to the gym 3 times a week.  He spends 1 hour each day lifting weight. Additionally, he also spends a third of his weightlifting time warming up and doing cardio each day.  How many hours does he spend at the gym a week?<n>Output: 4<n><n>Input: James has to refuel his plane.  It used to cost $200 to refill the tank.  He got an extra tank to double fuel capacity.  Fuel prices also went up by 20%.  How much does he pay now for fuel?<n>Output: 480<n><n>Input: The number of goals scored in a game against Barca by exactly two players last season accounts for 20% of all goals scored in the league. If the players scored an equal number of goals, and the total number of goals scored in the league against Barca that season is 300, calculate the number of goals each of the two players scored.<n>Output: 30<n><n>Input: Every day Tom drinks 5 12-oz cans of soda plus 64 ounces of water. How many ounces of fluid does he drink a week?<n>Output: 868<n><n>Input: Stella and Twinkle are filling up a truck with a capacity of 6000 stone blocks at the rate of 250 blocks per hour per person. They work for four hours and are then joined by 6 other people who also work at the same rate. How many hours did filling the truck take?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Elijah drank 8.5 pints of coffee yesterday. Emilio drank 9.5 pints of water yesterday. How many cups of liquid did the two boys drink yesterday?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Doris works at the Widget Factory in the packing department. She puts 3 widgets in each carton, which are 4 inches wide, 4 inches long, and 5 inches tall. She then packs those cartons into a shipping box before sending it to the loading bay. The shipping boxes are 20 inches wide, 20 inches long, and 20 inches high. How many widgets get shipped in each shipping box?<n>Output: 300<n><n>Input: Queenie earns $150 a day as a part-time clerk. She earns an additional $5 per hour as overtime pay. How much will Queenie receive for working 5 days with 4 hours overtime?<n>Output: 770<n><n>Input: Jodi starts off walking 1 mile a day for 6 days a week.  On the second week, she walks 2 miles a day, 6 days a week.  On the third week, she walks 3 miles a day, 6 days a week. Finally on the fourth week, she walks 4 miles a day, 6 days a week.  How many miles has she walked in 4 weeks?<n>Output: 60<n><n>Input: A club is going to get additional members so that they will have 5 more than twice their current number of their members. If the club has 10 members now, how many additional members do they need?<n>Output: 15<n><n>Input: Andrea buys herself a pony for her 30th birthday. She pays $500/month to rent a pasture for it, $10 a day for food, and $60/lesson for two lessons a week. How much does she spend on her pony in a year?<n>Output: 15890<n><n>Input:To locate a choker not located in a jewelry box or boutique where would you go? Choices:  A: jewelry store B: neck C: jewlery box D: jewelry box E: boutique<n>Output:		 C<n><n>Input:How many times does each of these values appear in the string “ABCDEFGHIJ”:  2. The ASCII value of ‘C’ 7. The ASCII value of a letter C followed by the letter G 3. The ASCII value of the alphabetically smallest letter 1. The ASCII value of one-third of the alphabet 6. The ASCII value of twice the alphabetically smallest letter<n>Output: 1  2  3  4  5  6  7<n>

If it sold $6000 worth of merchandise last year, how much does it sell this year?<n>Output: $18000<n><n>Input:[45, 30, 25, 8, 27, 9, 15, 48, 30] How many even numbered numbers are in this sequence?<n>Output: 9<n><n>### Solution:<n>[45, 3, 5, 8,, 6, 0]<n>How many even numbered numbers in this sequence?<n>### My Python code<n>import sys<n><n>if __name__ == "__main__":<n>    x = [int(i) for i in sys.stdin.readline().split(',')]<n>    ans = 2<n>    for i in x:<n>        l3 = len(i) == 3<n>        ans += 2 if  l3 else 1 <n>        ans += 3 if i%2 == 0 and l3 else 1<n>        ans += 4 if i%10 == 2 and l3 else 0<n>    print ans<n>

Choices:  A: carpenter's shop B: video game C: garage D: total number E: building<n>Output:		building<n><n>Input: If I have 3 pieces of fruit and 1 is equal to 6, and 2 is equal to 5, how would I write 7 pieces of fruit?<n>Answer: 7<n><n>#---------------------------------------------------------------------------<n>## Function: 1 to ______<n>This function takes a single number of the low end (starting at 1) to the high end.<n>### Input: <n>Input is the number you wish to change from one to the other.<n>### Output:<n>Output is the number with the start value of 1, and going to the end value of your choice.<n><n>## Example:<n>The example: 1 to 30<n>In this case from 1 to 32 in 30 steps (it would be faster to write it as 1 to 31 in 30 steps).<n>### Function:<n>def _____1to____ (number):<n>    # This function takes in the starting value number of the low end<n><n>    # This function will continue until it reaches the number of low end.<n><n>    for number in reversed(enumerate(range(number))):<n>        # I have to take this function and subtract 1 from it so that it subtract each value in the range.<n>        print(number-1)<n><n>#----------------------------------------<n>## Function:  ______ to ______<n>In our case, this is the same exact function as the _____1 to ______ function but this one goes from the high end to the lower end.<n><n>#-----Example-----<n><n>#-----<n># Example:   The example of this function is this:<n># 9 to 1. (So that means it goes from the high to the low,  instead of the other way around)<n># To get this number, I basically take my input number (in this example, it is NINE which is the highest number I want to go to the lowest number)<n><n># I take that number and I subtract from it to get my input number<n><n># Then I begin to subtract from it, one by one, until it is at the final value<n><n># In the end I have the number I wanted to go to.<n><n><n><n><n>#---------------------------------------<n>### ________________to ________________<n>#-----<n># This function is a combination of

Choices:  A: washing machine B: space shuttle C: blender D: disneyland E: surface of earth<n>Output:		A <n><n>Input: How much money do you have?<n><n>Output: 200<n><n># How do we check if its a palindrome?<n>def is_palindrome(s):<n>    start_index = 0<n>    end_index = len(s)-1<n>    result = 0<n>    # while I <= len(s)-1:<n>    #     if s[i]!= s[i+1]:<n>    #         result += 1<n>    #     else:<n>    #         result = 0<n><n>    while start_index < end_index:<n>        s1 = s[start_index]<n>        s2 = s[end_index-1]<n><n>        if s1!= s2:<n>            return False<n><n>        start_index+=1<n>        end_index-=1<n><n>    return True<n><n>import time<n>start = time.perf_counter()<n>palindrome = '11223344556677889900111212131314141515161617171818191920202121222223232424252526262727282829293030313132323333'<n>palindrome = is_palindrome('867' + palindrome[2:])<n>print(palindrome)<n>end = time.perf()<n>print('Execution Time: %f seconds' %(end-start))<n># palindrome = 'abcdefghi'<n># palindrome2 = 'fedcba'<n># print(is_palindrome(palindrome))<n>

Which number is greater, her dog or the sandbox? A: 1 B: 2 C: 3 D. 4E: 5 <n><n><n>### Instruction:Answer the questions below<n>A. How do I store an array in a file and in what format?<n>When you want to store something in a file that has the same type as what you are converting, that is when you can use the.serialize function if the data is of the type Object, and if it is of type String or boolean you can use the.toString function, here I have a string and I want to convert it to a file.<n><n>```<n>let str="hello world";<n><n>const file=fs.createWriteStream("helloworld.txt");<n><n>str.toString().serialize(file);<n><n>```<n><n>If you want to convert the data using another type you can do it like this and here I have to convert a type of Object and in order to do that I just have to write the convertion function with the type of data that I want to convert.<n><n>```<n>const arr=[1,2,3];<n><n> let str="hello world"; <n>```<n>A. When you want a string like " 123 hello! " (exclamation mark) and if you only want to get numbers like 1

If the players scored an equal number of goals, and the total number of goals scored in the league against Barca that season is 300, calculate the number of goals each of the two players scored.<n>Output: 30<n><n>Input: Every day Tom drinks 5 12-oz cans of soda plus 64 ounces of water. How many ounces of fluid does he drink a week?<n>Output: 868<n><n>Input: Stella and Twinkle are filling up a truck with a capacity of 6000 stone blocks at the rate of 250 blocks per hour per person. How many hours did filling the truck take?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Elijah drank 8.5 pints of coffee yesterday. Emilio drank 9.5 pints of water yesterday. How many cups of liquid did the two boys drink yesterday?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Doris works at the Widget Factory in the packing department. The shipping boxes are 20 inches wide, 20 inches long, and 20 inches high. How many widgets get shipped in each shipping box?<n>Output: 300<n><n>Input: Queenie earns $150 a day as a part-time clerk. She earns an additional $5 per hour as overtime pay. How much will Queenie receive for working 5 days with 4 hours overtime?<n>Output: 770<n><n>Input: Jodi starts off walking 1 mile a day for 6 days a week.  On the second week, she walks 2 miles a day, 6 days a week.  On the third week, she walks 3 miles a day, 6 days a week. Finally on the fourth week, she walks 4 miles a day, 6 days a week.  How many miles has she walked in 4 weeks?<n>Output: 60<n><n>Input: A club is going to get additional members so that they will have 5 more than twice their current number of their members. But you also picked 1.  You need to pick what you would like to do first.<n><n>Input: No, I'll finish 1 before I work on 2.  I would like to take

Choices:  A: next to the house B: keeping things in C: backyard D: farm yard E: ranch<n>Output:		A<n><n>#!/bin/python3<n><n># Problem Domain<n># This challenge was provided by Interview Query & CodeForces.<n># http://codeforces.com/contest/1221/problem/B<n><n># Solution Technique<n># Solution based on the algorithm given in http://codeforcesblog.wordpress.com/2011/07/22/short-version-of-quick-sort-in-python/<n># The same algorithm can be used for Medium - Hard problem domain - http://www.interviewquery.com/problem/Medium-Hard-Java-Puzzle-Problem-Domain-35/<n><n># Python version<n># python3 quick.py<n><n>import sys<n><n># Program starts here<n>sys.stdin = "1327598122735858435"<n>i = 0<n>n = int(sys.stdin.readline().replace(".", ""))<n><n>input = sys.stdin.read()<n>input1 = input.split()<n>while len(input1) > 0:<n>    curr_num = int(input1[0])<n>    if len(input1) == 1 or curr_num < 0:<n>        i += 1<n>        break<n>    i += curr_num<n><n>print(i)<n><n>

Which of the following will you calculate how many days it takes John to take a full bath?<n>```<n>We would have to ask the question as a mathematical equation, which is :<n>```<n>Days it takes John to take full bath <n>= John's bath time (in hours) / (24 hours)<n>```<n>So I will ask John for his bathtime in hours, and this will be the answer for question 20<n>```<n>21. You will be given 3 questions in total. Write a program to do the above.<n><n>import random<n><n>print("You can only attempt to answer your password 3 times")<n><n>password = ""<n><n>#You can enter any passwords<n>while True:<n>    password = input("Enter a password: ")<n><n>    if password == "32": #if the password is 32 then stop here<n>        break #break out of the loop<n>    else:<n>        print("Password must be valid or incorrect. You have attempted too many times")<n><n>    break #If not 32 then it will ask to enter a password again<n><n>    print("How many attempts you need") #this shows how many attempts is left for the user<n><n>if password == "32" or password == "321": #if the password equals 32 or 321 then this is the final password<n>    print("You have won the game. Good Luck next time!")<n>elif password == "2321" or password == "2311":<n>    print("You are still on track")#if the password equal to 2321 or 2311 then the game is still on<n>    print("you have 1 guess left")#this shows how many guesses is left for the user <n>else:<n>    print("You did not make it... you are incorrect 3 Times")<n><n>#You will be asked again if you want to play the game. If you enter 1 that means you want to continue playing. If enter 0 then you want to quit.<n><n>print("Do you want to continue the game or not

What is the surface area of the fabric measured in square feet?<n>Output: 975.6506624254<n><n>Output Format: Write an expression.<n><n>```python<n>def part1(n, dn, cn):<n>    return 1 + (n + (max(dn, cn) - min(cn, dn)))//2<n><n>def part2(n, dn):<n>    if (n == 2):<n>        return dn/2<n>    else:<n>        return part2(n - 1, dn) - dn + part2(n - (len(dn)//2), dn[::-1]) - dn<n><n>def part3(n):<n>    n_sum = 0<n>    lcs = ""<n>    i, j = 0, 0<n>    if (n < len(lcs)):<n>        while n > 0 and lcs[n-1] == lcs[n]:<n>            n_sum += 2<n>            n -= 1<n>        if (lcs[n]!= lcs[n+1]):<n>            return i<n>    dn = lcs.lower()<n>    cn = lcs.upper()<n><n>    while (i < n - (len(dn)/2) or j < n - (len (cn)/2)):<n>        print("{})".format(i))<n>        while (i + n

Choices A: zero B: one C: two D: infinite<n>Output: two<n>"""<n>import math<n>from typing import Dict, List<n>class Solution:<n>    def maxProfit(self, prices: List) -> int:<n>        profit = 0<n>        c = 0<n>        for item, p in zip(prices, prices[1:]):<n>            if p - item <= 0:<n>                c += 1<n>            else:<n>                profit = (c * p) - item<n>                c = 1<n>        return max(profit, 0)<n><n>    # @lc code=start<n>    def maxProfits(self, prices: [int]) -> int:<n>        total_profit = 0<n>        while len(prices) > 0:<n>            item = prices.pop()<n>            while item in prices:<n>                total_profit += prices.pop() - item<n>                item = prices.pop(-1)<n>            return total_profit == 0 and len(prices) == 0<n><n>    # @end  lc<n><n>    # @param prices:<n>    # @return:an integer<n>    def maxProphet(self, prices: Dict) -> int:<n><n>        dp_prophet = [0 for _ in range(len(prices))]<n>        for i in range(1, len(prices)):<n>            dp = list(range(i))<n>            dp_proph  = []<n><n>            profit = {k: 0 for k in range(i)}<n>            for j, price in prices.items():<n>                for k  in range(i):<n>                    if price > dp[i - 1]:<n>                        dp[k + 1] = i<n>                        profit[k] += price  - dp[i -1]<n>                    if price == dp[i -2]:<n>                        dps[k + 1][:len(dp) - 2] = [i - len(dp), dp, profit]<n>                        dps.append([k, [i - len(ap) for _ in range(i - len(ap))], profit

How many degrees Fahrenheit are there between these two temperatures?<n>Output:66.1<n><n>Input: If the year is divisible by 4, then the month is either April, May or September because those are the only months divisible by 4 that aren't January. If the year is divisble by 3, then its either a leap year of no leap year. Similarly, for the month. If it is a odd number divisible by 3, then it must be divisible by 9(9, 12, 15, 18 and 20 are the only odd numbers divisible by both 3 and 9) so it could be June, July or August. If the month is divisible by 5, then it is either a leap year or not a leap year and it could be January, March, May, July, August, October, or December. If it is divisible by 10, then it is either divisible by 4 and 5 or not divisible by 4 or 5 and it is either a leapers year or not a leaper year. So the possible months are Jan, Feb, March, April, June, July, August, September, October, November, December. There are 40 of these, so the answer is between 1 and 40.<n>Output:<n><n>Input: We have a set of 40 different kinds of cookies in a box that is divided into 4000 packages. Choices:  A: library B: parties C: kindergarten class D: bar E: school<n>Output:		A<n><n><n>#### My Code<n>```python<n>def solve(number, money, times, minutes, hours, day, wath, pounds, quarts, stones):<n>    def add(x,y):<n>        return float(y) + float(x)<n>    <n>    if type(number) is int:   <n>        while number/money!= int:<n>            money = money * 2<n>        return (int(number/money))<n>    if type(money) is int:    #if I need to type float<n>        times = times * 100<n>        number = 100*number<n>    if type(times) is int:<n>        numbers=int(number / money*times)<n>    else:<n>        numbers = number / float(times)<n> <n>    return numbers<n>    <n>    <n>if __name__== '__main__':   <n>    number = 12<n>    money=12<n>    output =solve(number, money, 3, 60)<n>    print(output)<n>    <n>```<n>Time:1 minutes<n>Space:38 kb<n>

Choices:  A: bus stop B: graph C: post office D: grass E: play<n>Output:		1<n>```<n><n>#### My solution<n>```<n>class Solution(object):<n>    def getX(self,a,a1):<n>        return a<n>    def getZ(self,a,z):<n>        return z<n>    def solution(self,n,m):<n>        ans = n<n>        if n == m:<n>            return n<n>        for i in range(2,m-n+1):<n>            ans += i<n>        return ans-m+n<n><n>    def solution2(self,n,k):<n>        ans = 1<n>        for i in [0,1,2]:<n>            if i in [0,n,n+1]:<n>                pass<n>            elif i in [n,n+k]:<n>                ans = i<n>                ans+=1<n>            else:<n>                ans -= 1<n>                pass<n>                ans<n>        return ans<n>```<n>

Write at least two complete sentences for each choice.<n><n>What is a mathematical expression?<n><n>Mathematical expressions are words that represent values of variables, such as $x^2$.<n><n>What is a variable in math?<n><n>A variable refers to an unspecified value of a number that can take on different values. For example, you could have the variable $x$ represent a numerical value different every time the sentence is read but that is constant over time. <n><n>Is Math an expression? Explain.<n><n>One would be very hard-pressed to give a simple yes or no to this question, especially since we can't easily answer "is cooking an expression"? but Math is usually the only thing we'd use in an expression, so no, math isn't an expression, but math is a concept within expressions.<n><n>How many expressions have the answer 6 or less?<n><n>Only four expressions have the answer  < 6, namely $4$, $0$, $-4$, and $e$, where $e$ is $2.7182818284590…$.<n><n>Is Math An Expression? Explain.<n>Mathematic is what one does in an expression, a math is the subject of what you do in the expression (since

Choice: A: Alex B: Bill C: Chris D: Charlie E: Calvin<n>Output: B<n>```<n><n>```python<n>def solution(s):<n>    input = s.split("\n")<n>    for line in input:<n>        print(line)<n>        command = line.split(" ")<n>        if (len(command) > 1):<n>            answer = command[1]<n>            if (answer == "Easy"):<n>                answer = 0 if (int(command[0]) == 0) else 1<n>            elif (answer == "Medium"):<n>                answer_type = "X" if ("X" in command[0]) else "O"<n>                answer = 1 if (int(command[-1]) == answer_type) else 0<n>            print("Ingredient and Number")<n>            print("Answer:", answer_type)<n><n>for i in range (1, 50):<n>    n = i * 3<n>    s = "Input " + str(i) + ":\n"<n>    s += "Example:\n"<n>    for l in range (n - 7, n + 7):<n>        s += str(l / 60) + "\n"<n>        s += str("minute\n")<n>        s += str((l / 60 / 60) / (60 / 4)) + "\n"<n>    s +="\nOutput:"<n>    print(s)<n>    s = input()<n>    print("------------")<n>    solution(s)<n>```<n><n>```<n>Input 3: Adam bought 3 kg of nuts (X) and 2.5 kg of dried fruits (O) at a store. Adam</h3><n><n>Adam bought 3 kilograph of nuts and 1 kilogram of dried fruits.  One kilogram of nut cost $12 and one gram of dried fruit cost $8. How much does he purchased?<n>Adam bought 15 pounds. It is equivalent to 3 kilos<n>Therefore,<n>Cost of nuts to Adam = 15*12<n>Cost of dried fruit to Adam  = 3*8<n>It is equivalent to 40.<n>Therefore,<n>Total purchase cost to Adam = 40+39 = 119.00<n><n>Answer:<n><h3>2. Johns</h3><n>He goes to the gym thrice a week. He spend 1 hour each day doing cardio. Additionally, he also spend a third of his weight lifting time warming up. Three in seven. Seven is equivalent to 1 week.<n>Hence, he spend 5 hours at the gym a day.<n><n>Therefore, He spend 12 hours at the gym for the week.<n><n>Answer:<n> <n><h3>3. James </h3><n>James has to refill the tank of his plane. It used to cost $100 per refill. He now buying an extra tank to double his fuel capacity.  Fule prices also goes up by 20<n>Fuel cost is multiplied by the capacity of your tank. How much did her purchases cost?<n>Answer: 56<n>Output:56<n><n><n>```python<n>import java.util.*<n><n>def answer1():<n>    d=[2,2.5]<n>    cash = 0<n>    for i in d:<n>        for j in d:<n>            product_cost= 12000*(i+j)<n>            cash += product_cost<n>    print("The cash was $"+str(cash))<n><n>answer1()<n>```<n>#### Input:<n>Johns goes to the gim at 3 times a week and lifts weight for 3 hours each visit. Choices:  Mac A: IBM B: Macintosh <n>Output: B<n>Import:  A company that sells software and hardware has a 25% markup.   To find this markup, multiply the list price by the markup percentage. That will be the selling price.  In the example below, John is selling a $125 dollar laptop.  How many dollars does he make selling that laptop?<n>Output:  $106.25<n>Import: A company that sells hardware and software has a 25 % markup percentage.  <n>To find this markup percentage, divide the price of the software or hardware that will be sold by 1 minus its markup percentage.  Multiply the markup percentage by the price.  That will be the seller's profit.  To find the number of products that will be sold, multiply the seller's markup percentage by the product price.  In the illustration below, the markup percentage for a computer system is 17 %.  How much does he make selling 100 computer systems that cost $500 each?<n>Output: 27,500 <n>

Land<n>B. A car<n>C. Money in the bank account<n>D. Bonds<n>Output: C<n>  <n>input: A bank account has a $1800 balance and $300 in interest. This means a purchase of $5,000 cash for inventory would not be recorded if an invoice was still outstanding.

The new pair of shoes are worth 50% of their olds’ prices when on sale, which makes them worth 10$ each. Now 40% of the old pairs on sale and the remaining old pairs are on discount at 30% of their original price. <n><n>Their prices are: (29 * 10 + 30%) * 4 = 150$<n><n>The new pairs’ prices = 0.5 * 150% (i.e. 150 * 50%/100%) = 120$<n><n>A 1500$ discount on sale makes the actual price of a pair 270$<n>###### End<n>Input: At a certain store yesterday the number of pairs of shoes on sale was 10 and the discount on the discount was 30%.  <n><n>The discount makes a pair worth 2/3 of their original price.  <n>In order to get the actual cost, the discount should be multiplied by the 2/3 = 2/3 * 0.75 = 0.5625.<n><n>The actual value of a pair is then (10 * (4 * 0.56) = 43.2.<n>###### End<n>The discounted price of a pair is 2/3 of its original price.
